Kenya on Saturday recorded 10 new cases of Covid-19 on from a sample of 3,827 tested in the last 24 hours. Health CS Mutahi Kagwe said in a statement said the positivity rate was at 0.3 per cent. Kagwe said that from the cases, 3 are Kenyans while 7 are foreigners. Six are males while 4 are females. The youngest patient is a 11-year-old while the oldest is 74 years old. In terms of county distribution, Nairobi recorded 8 cases, and Mombasa and Nakuru 1 case each. The total confirmed positive cases are now 323,531Â  and cumulative tests so far conducted are 3,547,755. Seven patients have recovered from from the virus, all of whom were under Home-Based Care and Isolation. The total recoveries now stand at 317,754 of whom 264,739 were under the Home-Based Care and Isolation while 53,015 are from various health facilities countrywide. The CS said that 14 patients are currently admitted to various health facilities countrywide, while 115 are under the Home-Based Isolation and Care program. No patient has been admitted to the Intensive Care Unit (ICU) or High Dependency Unit (HDU). No patient is on supplemental oxygen in the general ward. Vaccination status As of April 8, a total of 17,742,774 vaccines had been administered across the country. Of these, 16,224,720 doses have been administered to the adult population. The total number of vaccines administered in the last 24 hours is 13,553 while the total number of people fully vaccinated in the last 24 hours is 10,224. The proportion of adults fully vaccinated is now at 30.1 per cent.